> We inherited this tasty little number from an Australian friend of ours. The only thing he didn't explain was why he decided to call it Thor's Thunder Chicken.

Boil @water{350%ml} in a #pot{} with @salt{1/4%tsp}.

Finely chop your @red chilli{1}. Peel and finely dice your @ginger{1}(peeled and finely diced). Separate the leaves from the @pak choi{2}. Slice your @carrot{1} in two lengthways, and slice each half into 4 lengthways again. Now slice your carrot widthways into 4cm strips.

Add your @basmati rice{1} into the 350ml of boiling water and turn the heat to low. Cover the pan with a #lid{} and leave on the low heat for ~{10%minutes}. Finally, remove the pan from the heat and leave to rest for ~{10%minutes}. Don't peek under the lid until the 20 mins are up!

Chop your @British chicken thighs{4} into bite-size pieces. Combine the @muscovado sugar{1/2}%, ginger, chilli, @fish sauce{1} and @lemon{1/2} (zested and juiced) in a #bowl{}. Add the chicken and coat all pieces well in the marinade.

> A bullet chilli is quite spicy, so add more or less to taste. If you prefer less heat, remove the seeds before finely chopping!

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #pan{} on high heat. Once hot, fry the chicken for about ~{8%minutes}. Spoon excessive marinade over the chicken whilst cooking, this will help the chicken absorb all the flavours.

Meanwhile, bring 3cm of water to a gentle boil in a pan. Put a #colander{} over (but not touching) the water. Place the bok choy leaves and carrot in the colander with a lid or #plate{} on top. Steam the vegetables for around ~{3%minutes} or until soft enough to eat (but with a slight crunch left).

Serve your chicken on top of the rice, with the vegetables to the side. Garnish with a sprinkle of @coriander{2}(chopped).